The historical maps of the digital Bavaria Atlas, an offer of the geoportal Bavaria of the state government, are anything but current - but this is precisely why very revealing.
Especially when compared to current online maps.
Then it becomes clear how cities and municipalities in the distribution area of the Munich Mercury since the 19. Century changed.
The digital Bayern Atlas is a patchwork that you do not recognize as such.
More detailed maps, so-called original position sheets, were incorporated into the large overview map for cities and municipalities.
According to the Bavarian Surveying Administration, these were created between 1810 and 1864 and originated from the first survey of Bavaria.
Your client: Napoleon.
The French army leader occupied Bavaria since the spring of 1800 during the Second Coalition War with Austria.
Napoleon wanted an overview of the occupied country and commissioned a topographical reception of Bavaria - for military purposes, of course.
Even if the French troops with the peace of Lunéville of 9. February 1801 finally withdrew: It was today's neighbors who created the idea of a nationwide Bavaria map.
Elector Max IV Joseph continued to push the project forward, founded the "Topographische Bureau" - and thus the Bavarian Surveying Administration.
The Urpositionsblatt for Munich dates back to 1856 and, like everyone else, can be found on the website of the Bayerische Landesbibliothek.
The comparison earlier/today is most impressive in the example of the state capital.
The city has expanded in all directions and has grown together.
An example of this is Untersendling, which still appears relatively isolated in the map of 1856.
Sendling was incorporated as a Munich district 21 years after the map was created, i.e. in 1877.
Today, Untersendling is located in the middle of the city.
The houses of Untersendling are concentrated around 1856 along today's Plinganserstraße, which was only named after Georg Sebastian Plinganser in 1878, a leader of the uprising of the Bavarian peasants against Austria in 1705.
Where the West Park is today, you see nothing but fields - at first glance: When zooming in, a smaller map with dozens of lines and numbers appears: handwritten numbered pieces of land from the so-called "original recording", from which the property tax was derived.
Small plots no longer occupy farmers there today - but allotment gardeners of the "Land in Sonne" plant.
A large green area is emerging north of Untersendling.
The Theresienwiese, the scene of the Oktoberfest since 1810, was in the 19th. Century actually still a meadow - and not a concrete desert.
On the other side of the Isar, the historical map gives an insight into the history of psychiatric medicine.
In the Urpositionsblatt you can read in the area of today's district of Au-Haidhausen not only the street name "am Gasteig" or from the hill "Auf der Lüften" - but also in large letters "Irren Anstalt".
Yes, here on Auerfeldstraße, people with delusions were once locked up.
In 1858/59, the Munich district insane institution "Auf der Auer Lüften" was founded.
From 1872, Dr. Bernhard von Gudden the institution - the psychiatrist who is brought into connection with the death of King Ludwig II.
“He was progressive for his time, for example, ending the chaining of the so-called lunatics.
In addition, he has forbidden the staff to use violence against the inmates," says Hermann Wilhelm, head of the Museum Haidhausen, who has dealt with the institution for an exhibition.
There was initially room for 280 patients, later expanded to 500 places.
At some point, this capacity was no longer sufficient - the reason for the construction of the district asylum in Haar in 1905.
Since 2006, the Isar-Amper-Klinikum München-Ost, one of the largest psychiatries in Germany, has been located there.
Young people now meet in the Munich Salesianum on the site of the former Auer Anstalt.
The Order acquired the building complex in 1920 and converted it into a youth home with training companies.
West is the football field of the TSV München Ost, east residential buildings from the 1980s.
In 2015, the children's house "Casa Don Bosco" was built - in architectural style to the original building of the insane asylum, which had been destroyed in bombing raids in the Second World War.
The Marienplatz was listed around 1856 as the "Haupt Platz", the Kaufingerstraße was called "Kaufinger Gasse".
The Second World War also brought a decisive change in the heart of Munich.
The Allied bombs tore many holes in the city centre in December 1944.
A big one remained to this day - at the Marienhof.
The English Institute, small commercial buildings and a crypt chapel from the Middle Ages once stood at the Marienhof, where the preparatory work these days and on the 5th. April 2017 the ground-breaking ceremony for the second S-Bahn main line will take place.
