How football's financial rules affect Neymar's move to Paris
The rules aimed at preventing unhindered spending by European football clubs will not disrupt Neymar's world record transfer from Spain's Barcelona to France's Paris-Saint Germain.
Any consequences will yet come for Paris Saint-Germain from UEFA, as the governing organisation that oversees the European game has the power to ban teams from accessing the prestigious Champions League tournament.
Financial fair play rules launched by UEFA in 2011 mean PSG will eventually have to prove that the transfer of Neymar was funded without major losses.
Barcelona has paid 222 million euros ($262 million) to buy the Brazilian out of his contract, and Neymar will receive a salary that will be several tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some of the financial aspects of Neymar's move to France.
PSG can almost certainly loosen up the money for Neymar to sign and take him to a galaxy of other stars, given the team's energy-rich ruling family of Qatar.
Clubs are allowed to spend a lot of money on acquiring players, but must counteract with legitimate sources of income that allow them to take the break-even point in their football-related business.
FFP was conceived by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that had taken on enormous debt in their pursuit of success effectively cheated and risked themselves ruining themselves if banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, FFP shifted from focusing on the clubs' debts to monitoring their losses.
The change meant that the business model that Roman Abramovich originally used in Chelsea in 2003 - buying a club with potential and then investing heavily to improve the squad and build a global brand - should become a tougher affair.
During the current three-year FFP assessment period, which runs until 2018, clubs can accept losses of 30 million euros.
And although Platini fell out of favour from the presidency in 2015, his UEFA successor, Aleksander Ceferin, continues to campaign to deter excessive spending.
"Certainly FFP is not dead and we will certainly strengthen the rules for the future," Andrea Traverso, who is in charge of FFP at UEFA, told The Associated Press last week.
Although the PSG has paid Neymar's buy-out clause in a lump sum, it may distribute the amount for accounting over the duration of his contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so that the transfer fee for the next five years of EUR 44.4 million can be reported in the financial statements.
The first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014 has hit PSG along with Abu Dhabi, which is owned by Manchester City, with the heaviest sanctions.
PSG received a fine of 60 million euros (at that time $82 million), which was later lowered to 20 million euros - and it was ordered that the team members for the 2014/15 Champions League remain limited to 21 players instead of the otherwise normal 25 players.
UEFA is looking for clubs that could try to outsmart their financial supervision by inflating their revenues through companies linked to the owners of a club.
While a Qatari company could sponsor PSG if the value of sponsorship were to exceed standard market rates, UEFA would not allow this to be considered a legitimate income.
This is exactly what happened in 2014, when UEFA decided that the value of sponsorship of the PSA was bloated by the Qatar Tourism Authority.
It has been reported that part of the PSG payments to Neymar could come in via payments from the 2022 World Cup's organizing committee in Qatar.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 have denied that Neymar will become World Cup ambassador and such a maneuver could be easy to find out for UEFA regulators.
The previous sanctions against PSG mean that UEFA will be even more attentive to heed any attempt to circumvent the rules.
UEFA had no preparatory talks with PSG on Neymar's transfer, said on Thursday the people familiar with the situation.
They spoke to The Associated Press on condition of anonymity, as they were not authorized to discuss the PSG situation.
The latest published reports show that PSG achieved a profit of more than 10 million euros in 2015/16 with a turnover of 542.4 million euros.
The accounts for the last financial year have yet to be released.
PSG expect Neymar's arrival to be a boon for sponsorship deals, merchandising and jersey sales.
The club expects revenue to increase by at least 30 per cent after signing.
The Spanish league was clearly irritated to see one of the best football players go, and it tried to prevent Neymar's departure by claiming that PSG would hurt the FFP.
"It's a clear case of "financial doping" with the club and the state," La Liga's president, Javier Tebas, told Spanish daily AS regarding Qatar's ultimate ownership of PSG.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports tycoon, shares La Liga's reservations against a state that funds a club.
"It's the consequence of ownership and that has completely changed the entire landscape of football over the last 15 years," Wenger said Thursday.
“Once a country owns a club, anything is possible.
It will be very difficult to respect financial fair play because you can go different ways or have different interests when a country has such a big player to represent a country."
