The White House's decision to fly a naval helicopter to the South Lawn for an event that highlights American manufacturing last month is costing taxpayers up to $24,000, according to the military's data left to TIME magazine.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D, known as Marine One, when the president is on board, was at the heart of the event on the 17th. July at the White House with American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials took a tour of products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut-made helicopter was on display alongside a yacht from Maine, a Wisconsin fire truck and a Mississippi forklift.
The White House military office demanded the presence of the helicopter in a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, barely 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn, according to the records of the Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter.
"I just wanted you to be aware of this because it's such an unusual high-visibility event," the commander of the HMX-1 wrote to his supervisor, the deputy naval commander for aviation.
The message indicated that the helicopter was on the 17th. July arrived at around 7 a.m. on the South Lawn for the event at 3pm, and stayed until the lawn was cleared between 18:00 and 21:00 that evening.
The note adds that in case the departure from the White House should be delayed, a second crew would be needed for the return flight due to the restriction of service hours.
The original flight crew was at the helicopter during the event, while the unit's security personnel remained on the ground with the aircraft during the time.
The records provided to TIME did not clear whether a second flight crew was ultimately required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 asked if the event could violate the provision.
"One question we asked was whether it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were informed that this was not the case," the commander wrote.
"Sounds like you're locked," the deputy commander replied.
The "Made in America" event was designated as an official event by the White House and would not have been covered by the Hatch Act.
But official events also have political overtones.
At the event, the president gave an impetus for health care reform that was underway in the Senate, and he promoted efforts to curb government regulations.
The use of the aircraft, known as Marine One or Air Force One, for politically beneficial purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for the trip.
But requesting their use only for a photo surgery is unusual.
Trump conducted an investigation in February when the presidential plane was doing taxi services against the backdrop of his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account is full of messages complaining about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
"The White House is excited about the show "Made In America" - which shows products from all 50 states that are made by American workers with American materials," White House deputy press secretary Lindsay Walters said.
HMX-1 crews frequently conduct training flights in the Washington and South Lawn area to depose the U.S. president at the White House with precise centimeters.
When Trump was at the G20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 carried out 58 practice landings at the White House.
The flight for the "Made in America" event counted in the flight crew's training needs for the month, an official said.
Helicopter units flew an additional 11 hours that day for "non-presidency support missions."
The White House said taxpayers did not take the burden on any of the other props featured at the event.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company had not been involved in exhibiting the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not maintain budget records for the presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact cost of the event.
However, according to the U.S. Department of Defense's hourly rate for the 2017 budget year, the DoD refund rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
Records of the unit record the aircraft's flight time as 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility's home base in Quantico, Virginia.
The White House argues that the actual cost of operating the helicopter is well below that rate.
"Setting the cost to taxpayers based on estimates for the reimbursement rates is highly misleading," Walters said.
“These estimates include staff, maintenance, and many other hidden costs included in the annual funds.”
According to a 2015 RAND study, the reimbursement rates for DoD do not include personnel costs, but take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and contracting.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the helicopter's use for the event.
"The idea is to present things this week that are made in America," Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud that they contribute to our national security, and I assume that hundreds, if not thousands, of people are dependent on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we are all proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly for.
It is, of course, appropriate to highlight that."
